Stillness requires us to be anchored in the present moment, just the way the present moment is. And the past and the future can very easily pull us out of Stillness, because past and future notions are usually tied with expectations and outcomes.

They tempt us with wanting things to be other than what they are. And so we must enter this state of alert Stillness. It’s not passive. It requires full and pure attention.

Isn’t there a Stillness that emerges when you’re in pure, alert attention? Engaged, deep listening? 

We can easily find examples of this in nature. Nature reveals the wisdom of Stillness through movement. We wouldn’t say that nature is “still” according to the dictionary definition. There’s certainly a lot of movement in nature! 

But nature shows us Stillness *through* movement.

It’s so easy to want to fill in a blank after those two words, isn’t it? 

“I am…” well, fill it in! 

I am happy, I am sad, I am anxious, I am overworked, I am confused. The list goes on and on. But anytime we do that, what we’re doing is tying ourselves to circumstances.

Of course in the parlance of everyday conversation there’s less harm in it. But in the notion of identifying our true nature – and understanding our true nature – we want to use language carefully. Where we don’t identify with circumstances. Because when we don’t know who we really are, we create a made-up substitute.

The “I” of your story becomes an object. You talk about it like it’s not you, it’s someone else. We become Stillness not be rearranging the contents of life but by realizing the essence of who you are. 

#iam #iamhappy #being #stillness #consciousness #mindfulness #mindfulnesspractice #mindfulnessmeditation #awakening #enlightenment #awakeningconsciousness #higherawakening #higherconsciousness #yoga #meditation #manifestation

“I’ll be calm and peaceful and my life will be great IF…” you name it. All these external arrangements. We’ll never get there that way. There will always be something else.

This realization then is that you ARE life. Never defined by circumstances but by something underlying, pervasive, and continuous.

The thoughts, the ripples in the lake, they can come and go. You can be happy one moment, sad another. But they don’t define you.

You are not the happiness, you are not the sadness.

You are what underlies all of it. The clear, still lake in which the ripples arise.

There’s a real power in accessing Stillness with music. 

Author (and friend!) Joshua McGuire says, “The purpose of music is to bring us to silence. As we listen, we become the silence in which music happens. We disappear. Yet when the music is over we stand invited to a still fuller silence, not just the inner silence of our private experience but an immeasurable silence outside ourselves.

Silence is what is left over when everything is taken away; and from silence nothing can be taken away.”

Stillness is the essence of your being. Your essential nature.

Does that resonate with you?

As we head toward the end of another year, invariably we find ourselves thinking of what we want to improve upon in the new year. We may have made some big strides in 2022, or maybe we’re not as far along with our goals as we’d hoped.

But what helps drive us in service of these goals or intentions is our ability to focus. And while many of us seek Focus by creating optimal external conditions for it, those optimal conditions may not always exist. 

We always need Focus, though!

So how do you find Focus when the world around you makes it difficult?

Come with me on this exploration.

What are the characteristics of Resistance? It’s important to understand that no one is alone in this battle with Resistance. Everyone experiences Resistance and it shows up particularly when we’re upleveling ourselves. When we’re growing, exceeding the boundaries of what we know ourselves to be.

It’s not going to show up when we’re doing something that is easy for us to do. It’s only when we’re really pushing our limits, not when we’re under-achieving. 

Resistance seems to come from outside ourselves, but Resistance arises from within. It is self-generated and self-perpetuated.

And so we can consider Resistance to be this enemy within. 

#resistance #consciousness #mindfulness #mindfulnesspractice #mindfulnessmeditation #awakening #enlightenment #awakeningconsciousness #higherawakening #higherconsciousness #yoga #meditation #manifestation

Resistance will tell you anything to keep you from doing your work. It’s always lying to us. It understands nothing but power. 

It is not personal. There isn’t a force that’s trying to keep us down. It operates with indifference. It is a force of nature. It does not care in particular about us. It just is.

And it curiously shows up most strongly when we’re at the finish line. 

Resistance has no strength of its own. We feed it with power by our fear of it. And if we master that fear, then we conquer Resistance. 

#resistance #consciousness #mindfulness #mindfulnesspractice #mindfulnessmeditation #awakening #enlightenment #awakeningconsciousness #higherawakening #higherconsciousness #yoga #meditation #manifestation

What are the symptoms of Resistance?

We’ve all experienced procrastination. It’s the most common manifestation of Resistance because it is the easiest to rationalize. We don’t say, “I’m NEVER going to do that.” 

Procrastination says, “Let’s do it later. Let’s do it tomorrow.”

From an instance of procrastination to a habit of procrastination which becomes a life deferred.

Thus is the insidious nature of procrastination, because it takes us off the hook. Once it becomes habit, we never get what we need to do done. 

#resistance #consciousness #mindfulness #mindfulnesspractice #mindfulnessmeditation #awakening #enlightenment #awakeningconsciousness #higherawakening #higherconsciousness #yoga #meditation #manifestation

Now, procrastination usually gets a bad rap because we don’t have many words that are synonymous with it. 
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
But procrastination can serve a purpose! We push so hard, we’re constantly trying to achieve, we are always trying to outdo ourselves and others.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
We put so much pressure on ourselves. And in a way, there’s a quite unhealthy attitude in that regard. So I like to think of Compassionate Procrastination as taking a healthy break from the way we push ourselves day to day. 
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
#procrastination #consciousness #mindfulness #mindfulnesspractice #mindfulnessmeditation #awakening #enlightenment #awakeningconsciousness #higherawakening #higherconsciousness #yoga #meditation #manifestation

Some other symptoms of Resistance can include the distractions of pleasure. Actions like food, drugs, alcohol, sugar… anything that provides an immediate gratification.

How do we know when one of these distractions is a symptom of Resistance or not? We certainly need these things at different doses at different times. But how do we know when they’re operating in an unhealthy way?

There’s a simple test: the more empty you feel after this act, the more likely it is that Resistance is at play. Serving to pull you away from your path. 

#resistance #consciousness #mindfulness #mindfulnesspractice #mindfulnessmeditation #awakening #enlightenment #awakeningconsciousness #higherawakening #higherconsciousness #yoga #meditation #manifestation

Another symptom of Resistance is getting yourself into trouble.

When we look at it, it’s a cheap way of drawing attention to ourselves. And of course, getting ourselves into trouble prevents us from doing what we need to do. 

Creating drama with others or feeling like a victim can also be other forms of Resistance. 

The key is having awareness to know what you’re trying to distract yourself from.

Occasionally in life we’ll find ourselves stuck. In a creative rut. Or at worst, paralyzed with fear.

But this can actually be a good sign! It reminds us what we have to do. 

The more scared we are of something, the more sure we can be that we have to do it. We feel fear because there’s something at stake. Because we care about it. If it didn’t mean anything to us, we wouldn’t feel that fear. 

#fear #consciousness #mindfulness #mindfulnesspractice #mindfulnessmeditation #awakening #enlightenment #awakeningconsciousness #higherawakening #higherconsciousness #yoga #meditation #manifestation

So what happens when self-doubt rears its head? Self-doubt is really just an indication of our aspiration. 

This doubt – or fear – reflects love of a dream, of something bigger… or perhaps becoming someone bigger. 

The counterfeit innovator is wildly self-confident. But the real innovator is scared to death.

Resistance is directly proportional to love. The more Resistance you feel, the more love you have for whatever you’re resisting. 

The opposite of love isn’t hate, it’s indifference. The more Resistance an unmanifested project presents, the more important it is for you. And the more important it is, the more gratification you’ll feel when you finally do it.

What if the athlete said that? The best athletes play hurt. They’re always in some kind of low-grade pain. There’s no need to wait until we’re 100% perfect because that day will most likely never come!

Are we just at the whim of things that are shiny and catch our attention or are we able to impose agency? 

The great story of Ulysses in Homer’s Odyssey is that Ulysses and his fellow boatsmen knew that as they went through the waters there were sirens who would lure sailors with their song. In order to avoid this lure, Ulysses commanded all of his sailors to put beeswax in their ears so they would not hear the sirens and continue to sail on past the rocky shores.

All of the sailors followed the command, except for Ulysses. He *wanted* to hear the siren’s song. But he knew that he would be tempted. And so commanded his sailors to tie him to the mast so that he couldn’t steer the ship and also commanded them not to listen to him no matter what he said.

And he did. And they did. And so he got to hear the siren’s song.

I bring this up because there’s a notion called a Ulysses Pact: a pre-commitment, and the power that comes with a pre-commitment. You remove a future choice to overcome impulsivity.

We can also employ time-blocking strategies like the Pomodoro Technique to focus our energy in shorter bursts in order to be more productive and effective.

I’d like to take some time now to discuss a key component of the human experience: BELONGING.

Animals in the wild rely on one another for protection. They travel together, they eat meals together, and in some instances they even raise their young together. They instinctively understand that a member of their pack who’s been separated from the group risks becoming prey.

And, in extreme scenarios, the weakest of the group can be left behind to prevent the entire group being put at risk.

Humans may have evolved but we are ultimately pack animals ourselves. On a deep, primal level, we understand that to be “other” means we run the risk of being cast out from the pack. 

And unconsciously we also understand a fundamental truth that separation often means death.

But, as we discovered in our exploration of Courage, there are moments in life when we are called to something greater. When the pain of fitting in is deeper than the pain of standing out.

The longest and most meaningful relationship you’ll ever have is the one most of us spend our whole lives avoiding: the relationship you have with yourself. As we’ll explore this month, you can’t truly belong until you have fully accepted yourself, exactly as you are.

Once you’ve done that, you’re never truly alone. You’ll call others toward you. This is true Belonging. Let’s journey together.

To have the innate instinct and drive to belong means that on some level, we must experience the default of feeling separated, or that we don’t belong.

It’s a traumatizing moment!

That’s when the narratives and the woundings begin. The stories we tell ourselves:

I’m not smart enough.
I’m not good enough.

All of that is going to be alienating.

“Trust is the glue of life. It is the most essential ingredient in effective communication. It’s the foundational principle of all relationships.” – Steven Covey

When we take a meta view of it all, trust really is the foundation for all human connection.

How slow or fast is the connection? How efficient is the connection? How “stuck” is the connection?

All of this depends on the level of trust. It operates in direct proportion to the efficiency of that connection.

That’s true for institutions, global dynamics, and it’s true in our personal relationships. Trust can speed everything up, smooth everything out, remove friction and resistance. It can provide an ease of relating.

#mindfulness #mindfulnesspractice #mindfulnessmeditation #awakening #enlightenment #awakeningconsciousness #higherawakening #higherconsciousness #yoga #meditation #manifestation #trust

Steven Covey goes on to say: “Trust is the one thing that affects everything else you’re doing. It’s a performance multiplier which takes your trajectory upwards for every activity you engaged in…”

It can really be applied to all areas of your life. It’s a horizontal game-changer.

So where does our relationship with Trust begin? 

It would have to go back to early childhood, to our relationships with our caregivers. Those early childhood relationships shape our ability to trust others and trust ourselves.

We can call that Original Trust.

The imprint happens at this very young and impressionable age.

Certainly not even at a conscious age. The relationship we have with those caregivers will have defined our innate and instinctual ability to trust from that early stage.

When you find yourself having a thought that keeps you from trusting, stop and ask yourself:

1. Is it true?
2. Can I absolutely know that it’s true?
3. How do I react when I believe that thought?
4. Who would I be without the thought?

Can you turn around that thought and introduce the opposite?
